Native script: nertruku (abl.sg.m. + postpos. -co(m), Ia 32). Latin script: nertru (abl.sg.m., VIb 25), nertruco (abl.sg.m. + postpos. -co(m), VIb 37, 39).
variant: wdnk, f. wdnc/wdnyc, pl. wdnyc/wdncy; more general use

Singulative. Seems to be the Swadesh term in Middle Breton.The Catholicon (1499) translates French 'nuée', Latin 'nebula, nubes'.Modern Breton koabr(enn) is rather a black cloud, cf. Favereau Dict. 418.The Modern Breton terms koumoul (from Latin cumulus) and koguss (from Old French cocusse, a kind of hood, from Vulgar Latin coqucia) are attested only from Early Modern Breton onwards.
There is also a derivative 'ďotka' 'small child, child' attested.
see also emphatic negative nepe 'not' with particle -pe.
According to Schrijver (1995, 53-55) a compound containing 'horn' as a second member.

Looks like a quite technical term,not like the everyday word;(lit. the one of under age; der/die Unmündige; however, Vd 13.48 "the dog is sleepy like an "apǝrǝnāyuš" speaks in favour of "child", i.e. "under age" as ADJ and N was lexicalised as "child". < a- + pǝrǝna- + āyu- "not full age"; another term that comes up is frazan-/frazanti- which will become the regular term for child)
Native script: numneís (gen. sg., Sa 17), num(nud) (abl. sg., Cp 32)
superlative form. Native script nessimas (nom.pl.f., Cp 24), nessimass (acc.pl.f., Cp 31), Latin script: nesimum (gen.pl.n., TB 17, 31), nesimois (abl.pl.n., TB 25).
Middle English dien, presumably a borrowing from Old Norse deyja.
From PToch. *śəṣə́rə < PIE acc. *g̑ʰés-r-m̥ with contraction. Exact relationship with TA tsar uncertain, though most scholars derive them from the same PIE source.
It is not clear if it is 'white cloud' or 'black cloud' (only).
*-ye/o-present. Cognate with Skt. arṣ- ‘to stream, to flow’.
Only attested in gloss "enc hehen da me?" BN lat. 11411 fo 102b. Existence controversial.
Lit. 'to kick a hole' but means 'to dig with a spade'; also 'to kick'.
Prob < OFr diguer 'to make dyke, hollow out the earth, < Gmc, cf. Du dijk 'dyke'.
Palaeo-Umbrian forms. Native script: matres (gen.sg., Um 17, Um 19, Um 18). Latin script: (gen.sg., Um 7).

The Geldner edition displays nǝmǝδka, which is rejected by Bartholomae (1904: 1068). The context is about offerings which are brought to the fire by Daēva worshippers. It is a kind of firewood „which is called nǝmaδka“. It could be a kind of halophyte. These were probably considered unfitting for a proper ceremony.
Cf. Toch. A kärn- 'id.' Toch. B /pyak-/ has a similar but more specific meaning 'strike (down), beat (a drum)'.
From Middle English, from Old Norse drit 'excrement, mud, filth'
According to (Sychta 1967-1976) the word was rarely used. It is likely that its frequency raised due to Polish influence.

Native script neip (Cp 37), Latin script: neip (TB 15), perh. a shortened form < ne-ī-kʷid 'nothing', cf. Latin script: nei (TB 20). Used of indicative negation. Cf. Latin script ni (TB 8, 13, 17, 29, etc.) used of prohibitive negation.

gloss: stand, remain, be placed (in a standing position)

notes: Extremely common element of personal names.

Only form attested. Claimed loanword from Indo-Iranian, but just as likely inherited; denominative to śerwe 'hunter' (cf. Toch. A śaru). Latter prob. a vrddhi-derivative of PIE *k̂erwo- 'stag' (Jasanoff apud Nussbaum 1986:8), rather than **g̑ʰu̯ēr-u- (so Adams 2013:694).

The infinitive is a compound of Old Breton guid-, Middle Breton gouz- 'to know' and -but, the verbal noun of 'to be'. Apart from the present and imperfect indicative, the finite forms are compounds of these two verbs as well.
following its attestations in the Nerangistan (missing in Bartholomae 1904)
Etymology much debated, but probably ultimately connected with PIE *me-, obl. stem of 1sg. pronoun. Cf. Toch. A näṣ (m.), ñuk (f.).

HL kwissa- iterative of luw. kuu̯ai̯a- (LIV² 130 n. 5a). Also attested in Hittite texts. See also luv. nahhi-, nahassa- 'fear' and hitt. naḫḫ- 'to become afraid, fear, be respectful, careful' (cf. LIV² 449). Native script form ku-wa-ya-am-ma-an-za (CL) is a participle.

Native script: numem (nom./acc.sg., Ib 17 (2x)). Latin script: nome (nom./acc.sg., 13x between VIa 30, - VIIa 47), nomner (gen.sg., VIb 54,59, VIIa 12,48), nomne (dat.sg., 40x between VIa 24 - VIa 51), nomne (abl.sg., VIa 17), nomneper (abl.sg. + postpos. -per, 40x between VIa 23 - VIIa 35).
Also 'cloud'. Either cognate with Slav *mьgla 'darkness, mist' or borrowing from Lat nebula 'cloud'. Orel prefers the Slavic origin.
Formally a diminutive. The non-diminutive form 'pos' is used rarely and in a more specified meaning.

gloss: to count, Latin computare; to tell, to relate
notes: The Catholicon has also niveraff 'nombrer', Latin numerare.

HL suran-. Cognate with Hitt. karāu̯ar / karaun-. As a proper noun, CL attests the abl.-instr. with Sumerogram SI-na-ti. The genitival adjective za-ar-u̯a-ni-i̯a-ti allows a stem form *zaruu̯ar / *zarun- to be reconstructed. HL attests suran- 'horn' "CORNU+RA/I" su+ra/i-sa (nom.-acc.sg.).

Bartholomae (1904: 905) translates "(Fleisch)speise". However, its attestations in the Nerangistan and the Frahang ī ōīm (F 463) suggest the meaning "meat". The attestation in the Frahang ī ōīm (Klingenschmitt 1968: 76) of *kǝrǝfma- is uncertain.There is also gauu-, cf. Bartholomae (1904: 507) under II.2 „das was das Rind liefert, Fleisch“.
Attested only in acc. pl. pärseriṃ.

noun, from PCelt. *fotlo-, cf. lat. pōculum

2 sg. imperative. The attestation make an impression that the word/form in the meaning 'to come' was restricted only to imperative.
Attested acc. sg. waräñc (with orthographic variation).
Suppletive stem ṣem- in rest of masc. paradigm. Fem. sana, acc. somo.
Middle English drinken, Old English drincan

Also 'leg'. Borrowed < Rom *kamba ~ *gamba 'leg, although direction of borrowing may be uncertain.

Root /ləka-/, alternating with /lʲəka-/ in the preterite. Pres. act. stem /ləka-ṣṣ-ə-/ ~ /ləka-sk-e-/, otherwise identical to subj. /ləka-/. Iptv. forms to /pəlka-/, cf. Toch. A nonpres. /plkā-/.
EXCLUDE. use of demonstrative (dat.Pl.) as pronoun.
superlative form, Latin script: nesimei (loc.sg.n., 2x in VIa 9)
From *exs-id-bal-ni 'throws it (out)', cognate with Gk. bállō /lexeme/18968/

Deities associated with Ceres through the attributive adjective kerríiúís. Usually interpreted as 'rain-deities' (Lat. dat.pl. imbribus, nom.sg. imber 'rain, heavy rain, rainstorm'. See further notes in cognate coding. Attestations: native script anafríss (dat.pl., Sa1 A9, B12)
Native script: neip (IIa 4, Va 29), Latin script: (VIa 27, 36, 46; VIb 29; VIIb 3)
In some other dialects a form 'cyc' is used.

Seems to be the Swadesh term in Middle Breton, rather than squeiaff, squeigaff, Modern Breton skejañ. The latter means 'to cut off, to cut into pieces, to make an incision (chirurgical term)'.The Catholicon translates squeiaff, squeigaff as 'coupper, Latin amputare, cedere'.
Middle English drie, Old English drȳge
expected aδam; oblique and clitic stem ma-

Nor borrowed from Latin, cf. Klingenschmitt, Albanian numerals.
Meaning and cognacy doubtful. Bartholomae's root ⁴raod- 'fliessen' does not exist, and initial *sr- ought to become θr- in Avestan.
the homonym zyam is probably more original
element BIT related to BUT/BOT in /cognate/868/?
Native script: destrst (nom. sg. f. + íst, Cp 8), a contraction of *destru íst = Lat. dext(e)ra est.
Native script: víú (nom.sg.). Many attestations, cf. Untermann (2000:860) for full range.
Related to IE *ous-, cf also Lat auris, Lith ausis, Latv auss.
It occurs in the texts in contexts like 'in the belly, full belly...' and not for decribing the '*outer* part of the body'.
< Pr. Alb. *bara, related to Lat far 'sort of grain, spelt'.

Lyc. B *tbi, cf. tbisu 'twice' (: Lyc. A kbihu)
Native script: rufru (acc.pl.m., Ib 24), rufra (acc.pl.f., Ib 27). Latin script: rufrer (gen.sg.m., VIa 14).
The word is not attested in the Canon but in younger texts only.
šwk used for the "nail" of a camel

Native script: testru (abl.sg.m./n., III 23, IV 15), testruku (abl.sg.m. + postpos. -com, Ia 29), testre e (loc.sg.m. + postpos. -en, IIb 27, 28). Latin script: destram e (A.sg.f. with postpos. -en, VIb 49), destruco (abl.sg.m. with postpos. -com), destre (loc.sg.m. + postpos. -en, VIb 50), destr e (loc.sg.m. with postpos. -en, VIb 4).
Native script: deíkum (pres.inf., Cp 36). Latin script: deicum (pres. inf., TB 10), deicans (3.pl.subj.pres., TB 9), dicust (3.sg.fut., TB 14).

the pronoun occurs in orthotonic as well as enclitic position.
Middle English ere, Old English ēare

The meaning 'count' is not attested in the Canon (here only the meaning 'read' is attested). However, derivatives ('число, чисмѧ') show that the verb had the meaning 'count'. In this meaning it is well attested in later texts.

Native script: staít (3.sg.pres., TA B 22), stahínt (3.pl.pres., Cp 25), stahint (3.pl.pres., Cp 25), staíet (3.pl.pres., CA B 31, Cp 24), stai[ (parsing unclear, Sa 17), staieffud (3.sg.pf.?, Cp 31), eestínt (3.pl.pres., TA B 1.3) w/ preverb ē-.
Alternative lexemes are 'хладьнъ' and 'зимьнъ'. 'хладьнъ' is more like 'cool, fresh'. The primary meaning of 'зимьнъ' is 'winter, wintry'.
fodiō, fodere, fōdī, fossum; identical with /lexeme/20517/.
Native script: úlleís (gen.sg.m., Cm 13), ulum (acc.sg.m., Cp 37), úlam (acc.sg.f. Cp 36), ulas (gen.sg.f., Cp. 37). Latin script: olu (gen.pl.m., Cm 15).
‘insensitive, insensate, dull, numb, deaf, stubborn' < IE *dheu- 'to die, wear away, fade', cogn. with terms for 'die' in /cognate/201/

Third Catechism. EV: towis. Gr: taus

Most frequently attested in the Canon (over 700 times). Alternative lexemes ('дѣлати, дѣяти, дѣиствовати, etc.') are not so frequented and some of them seem to mean more like 'to work, to operate, to make'.
realizations of /h/ are variable, and while it is perceived as a phoneme it is often omitted phonetically, especially in natural and rapid speech

From IE *h3(e)kuih1 > PALb *atsiwi, a form of dual related to - inter alia - Skt aksi, Lith akì.

dyth wyth = Late Middle Cornish, AF dydh
Native script form is 3.sg.pret. Cf. HL: AUDIRE+MI-(ma)-ti-. Denominative from tūmman(t)- 'ear'.

From PAlb *be(r)ja derived from IE *bher- 'to strike, to beat'. Aorist form rashë goes back to PAlb *rausa, a sigmatic aorist of IE *reu- 'to tear', cf also Skt ravate 'to smash', Lat ruo 'to tear', etc. (ra, ran = INF.)
An alternative lexeme could be 'пьрѣти сѧ' but it is not attested in this meaning in the Canon.
Attested only in the derived adjective śiñcatstse.
same as ‘cold’ below; used as part of the verb ‘freeze’ below
Latin script: uirseto auirseto 'seen (and) unseen' (past pass.part., nom.sg., VIa 28, 38, 48, VIb 30).
< Pr. Alb. * ka tu, including pronominal stem *ka < IE *kuo- and adverbial *tu, cf. Skt tú 'now'.

no etymological information in Morgenstierne (1974); vocalism is closer to Parthian than to Persian

same as ‘ice’ above; used as part of the verb ‘freeze’ below
unclear meaning, but cf. Luv. ziti- 'man' (Laroche 1987:238). Another possible meaning is 'son-in-law' (Schürr 1999:25).

Used to denote a flat nose as well as for instruments like a sword of a sickle.The latter usage is however only attested from Early Modern Breton onwards. If the Middle Breton meaning was 'flat', tougn is not the Swadesh term.Etymology: Like Welsh twm 'cut, broken' from Vulgar Latin *tondere 'to shear' (Deshayes 2003, 728).

Middle English fallen, Old English feallan

Either (i) < PAlb *dzel-ma, from Alb dhallë 'buttermilk', or (ii) < IE *deh2- 'to flow' > all 3 Balkan IE languages, see also Gk cognate and Arm tamuk 'wet'.

Cf. klautkäṣṣäṃ 'turns', causative pres. of /klawtka-/ 'turn, become', ultimately denominative to klautke 'turn, manner, behavior'. according to Morgenstierne 2003: 83 triu „bitter“ Morgenstierne 2003: 83, it should actually be trix [„with i from *tirw (> triw, q.v.)“]. triw would actually mean „buttermilk; a kind of sour cheese“ < *tiwra- cf. Skt. tīvra- „pungent“. The trix word would belong to NP talx < *taxra-.

The definite article and the deictic particle se constitute a discontinuous marker used as an attributive demonstrative. The phrase consists of article + noun + particle, e.g. an map se 'that son', e-n ty se 'in that house'. Note that Middle Breton has a threefold deictic system: an ... man 'here (near me) / this', an ... se 'there (near you) / that', an ... hont 'yonder'.

The lexeme 'hoditi' has normally the meanign 'fit, suit' in . There is also a secondary meaning 'hit, hit something by throwing' but this lexeme is not the Swadesh term in Old Czech yet. 'kydnúti, kydati' is less frequented and occurs in the context of 'dung, mud, dirt'. 'metati' is typically imperfective.
Possible alternative lexemes are 'ledvie' and 'bedro'. However, it seems that 'thigh' is not their main meaning.

The form is arguably related to (or influenced by) /cognate/145/.  Mechanically, it appears that the reflex of PIE *tuH 'you.sg' was pluralized, i.e. *du-kʰ.  However, such pluralization is unprecedented in the Armenian pronominal system, and it seems more likely that the opposition *du (< PIE *tu) vs. *(ǰ)uk' from PIE *iuH-s /cognate/5822/ (Lith. jū̃s , Goth. jus, etc.) was substituted by du vs. dukʰ.

However, in the local meaning it focuses more on the place where the addressee of a utterance is and it can also mean 'near to here' or 'in sight'. Farther 'tu' is semantically more complexe (it has also a temporal meaning 'the other day, soon' and a meaning 'in this case, in such a case').

from je 'that' (pronoun, not determiner) and -ci. The origin of -ci is the same as in Iron. The pronominal root je is from PIr. *ay-, cf. Av. ayəm. This root does not exist in Iron at all, but is clearly a Digor archaism. Proto-Ossetic apparently had three degrees of deixis; Digor still has them in the determiners (a-ci, je-ci, wo-ci), but merged je and wo into a single paradigm in the pronoun. In Iron *je disappeared entirely.
In the Canon it is attested in prepositional phrases with the meaning 'on the left' only. However, in younger texts it is attested as a adjective 'left' too.

'лѣсъ' is attested twice in the Canon. There are alternative lexemes: 'дрѧзга' (attested once as 'woods, grove, coppice'), 'дѫбрава' (attested five times as 'grove, coppice, oak woods, deciduous forest') and 'лѫгъ' (attested once as 'woods, grove, coppice').

gloss: m. f. ~ mákṣā- f. ~ mákṣikā- f.

notes: Alternative lexemes are: 'товщ' (dialectal) and 'сало' ('pork fat, bacon').

Strohmeyer 1983 concludes that, in contrast with the generic term t'ṙč'un ‘bird, any living thing which flies’, haw has a more complex, although smaller, semantic range which primarily includes birds which are useful to men.
Traditionally pronounced [kəts(ɑn)ɛm]; cf. կսկիծ ks-kic [kəskits] 'pang, (twitching) pain'; կիծ kic 'bite! (2sg)'.
AF ṣunǰ. Alternation š ~ ṣ is typical for loans from Persian/Tajik.
also /ˈti(ɣ)alo/ or /ˈti(ɣ)ala/; cf. MG τι ‘what’ + λογής ‘kind’
Domesticated bird, basic term 'bird' in written usage.
Traditionally pronounced [pʰətʃʰɛm]; Cf. փուք pʿu(-)kʿ [pʰukʰ] 'breath; wind; fart; puffiness'.

Alternative lexemes are 'порох' and 'курява'. The choice is not straightforward. According to a native speaker 'пил' is the most generic and neutral of them and can be used both for 'dust outside' and 'building internal-dust', although it shows some tendency to the meaning 'building internal-dust'. The other words usually refer to 'dust outside' but are slightly expressive.
Plurale tantum; Traditionally pronounced as two syllables, i.e. [ˈkuɾ.tsəkʰ].

Probably etymologically connected with Gk. έλαχύς 'gering', Skt. raghu-'eilend, schnell, geschwind', laghu- 'leicht, unschwer, gering', Lat.levis 'light' etc., and the semantically close cognates ON lunga, Russ.legkoje 'lung'.
stem variant uruϑβan; in the Frahang ī ōīm for "belly" (probably rather stomach), the Frahang ī ōīm also gives uruuata- (sole attestation F 190)
Traditionally prononced [ʃəɲˈtʃʰɛm]; cf. շունչ [ʃuɲtʃʰ] 'breath; soul; person'.
Attested both in the material and religious/moral meaning.
Older form dmāna, cf. also dam- N.m "house"
Has a broad range of meanings (innards, insides, including the heart and so on), but it seems to be the basic term.

i.e. 'ground, soil', also 'burial plot, cemetery'. Connected with OCS polje , Russ. póle , etc. 'field', Russ. pol m. 'floor', ORuss. polъ m. 'foundation', Russ. pólyj 'open, bare, empty'. Alternatively, possibly linked to Lat. solum.
In contexts like: 'Rice/other grain swells when it cooks.'
Only attested as present participle pišaṇt (cf. Cheung 2007: 292); in the phonemic field was written "r̩naːti" which makes no sense to me (TJ)
An alternative lexeme 'мислити' is used in more philosophical meaning.
More frequent in (early) RV than pāpá-
It.; but also the non-cognate Ap. /(i)ˈkro̞/, /aˈkro̞/.
Often also vánaspáti- 'lord of the wood' = 'tree', later the general technical term
Also 'mist'. In dialect, also 'white fleck'. Connected to 'white' /cognate/1190/.
'wide, extensive, broad, extended, spacious, roomy; not narrow'
Linked with the Germanic word for 'hard, steady, strong, firm, dense': OIc. fastr , OHG festi , fasti , Engl. fast , etc.
Inf. μυζᾶν.  Often found with compounded prefixes, e.g. ἐκμυζάω, cf. Il. 4.218 αἷμ’ ἐκμυζήσας 'after having sucked the blood (out of an arrow wound)'.

the Frahang ī ōīm also gives rāna-, Klingenschmitt (1968: 74), Bartholomae (1904: 1523) "der äussere Teil des Oberschenkels; Oberschenkel (überhaupt)"; checking the attestations: there is one indication that says "inbetween the unclean thighs" (sexual intercourse with a menstruating woman; Vd 16.16); for haxti- there is one instance where Bartholomae interprets it as part of a fixed expression: Mark und Bein, Fleisch und Blut (Y 53.7). rāna- seems to refer to the inner muscle.
cf. bhas- 'to chew', RV bhásman- adj.
Denominative of քուն kʿown 'sleep' from PIE *su̯op-no-.

Connected with OIc. hjarn n. < *her(z)na- 'frozen snow', OHG hornung 'February', Russ. serën , serená 'crust over snow', séren' , Ukr. serén 'frozen hard snow', Lith. šer̃kšnas m. < *k̂(e)r-sno- 'hoarfrost', adj. 'grey, whitish', šarmà < *k̂or-meh2- 'frost', etc. (?).
Not yet the default word for 'bird'
Alternative form χτες [xtes].  Fricative [xθes] reintroduced from literary spelling χθες (katharevousa).
Cf. բարակ ճանապարհ '(lit.) thin, i.e. narrow, road'.
Inf. κεντεῖν.  IE *kent-, knt-o, = Lat. CENTRUM (Matasovic 2007: 673)
From PIE *bud- 'to swell', same etymology as ptuk 'nipple; bud'.

gloss: return to the surface of the water

notes: often first member of a compound
Late form but widespread in dialects.

gloss: I.e. 'to wipe off; sponge'; also 'to clean; purify; sanctify, consecrate'
notes: A denominative of սուրբ sowrb 'clean; pure; holy'; cognate with Ved. śubhrá 'brilliant, shining; beautiful'.
gēǰ From QIE *gwhe/oidh-io-, cf. Russ. žídkij , SCr. žídak , etc. 'liquid, watery' although this is not fully accepted by Martirosyan.
Traditionally pronounced [kərtʰuŋkʰ]; cf. կուռն kowṙ-n (trad. pron.) [kurən] 'back; pelvis; arm' (from an orig. "curved body part" or the like).

gloss: i.e. 'the Sun' as the heavenly body

notes: From Proto-Armenian *əndi (< PIE *h₂ent-i) prefixed to *tʰɑ-n-ɑ- (< PIE ?*pt-n(e)-h₂-).
In this specific meaning, the preposition governs the accusative.
Arguably cognate with Gk. αἴθω "I ignite, kindle; burn, blaze".
Causal conjunction. AF ὅτι, hóti.  See notes in cognate class. lit. 'through what thing'
Inf. πλεῖν. More commonly used to mean "sail", etc., but also "float" (of inanimates in the sea).
An alternative lexeme could be 'чадо' 'čado'. It is attested only once in a vocative phrase 'my child!' and relatively late.
It is a place name. The word for 'forest' as a appelative is probably attested in another manuscript but it is uncertain.
It refers to 'fish guts' in the manuscripts.

The word is attested in a tiny glossary with a Karelian gloss 'belly'. (DND 2004) suggests that it reffered to the belly part of an animal pelt. However, it doesn't result from the source itself. Anyhow, the word 'животъ' (as in the modern Russian) is attested only in the meaning 'things, fortune'.

gloss: to hide not to be seen

notes: manner of movement: he came running (non-telic verb)
also 'stomach' (in other dialects and Standard Alb. its primary meaning)
Orel gives nëmëroj 'to number, to count'. Loan < Lat numerāre 'id'.
< Pr. Alb. *dega, etymologically related to IE *dhegʷʰ- 'id' and its continuants.
Borrowed < Lat arēna id. Holm, however, prefers an alternative etymology < IE *er- 'sand, locker' (cf Lat rārus) but has no recent cognates.
Borrowed < Gmc *skurtaz 'short': OHG scurz, OE sceort 'id'.
Variants: këthatër(r), k(ë)thadër.Orel wants a derivative in -tër from kthej 'to turn', what is doubtful for semantic and morphological reasons (-tër is not productive for deverbal agent nouns).
Uncertain. Demiraj proposes connection to PIE *(h1)reh1p- ‘to creep' and a formation with  intensive-privative prefix v(ë)-. (doubtful)
prefixed Alb. *ambëlt < *an-blit < *(H)en-mlit- ‘which has honey (in it)’ with epenthesis or dissimilation.
The lexeme 'snóčɪ' means 'yestarday in the evening'.

It has two synonimical meanings 'narrow like a narrow river, road, table etc.' and 'narrow with a connotation of very little or too litte space, tight'. Probably the first meaning predominated but it is not entirely clear.
Also 'to suck'. piva (aor); pirë (participle). related to IE *po(i)- 'to drink'.
Most likely connected to (extended) Standard/Tosk gjoks.
(r/n-stem) pattar/pattan- 'wing, feather' (*petH- 'to fly'). Cf. also partāu̯ar/partaun- 'wing, feather'.
Another form is qym. Borrowed < Lat cyma 'young shoots (of cabbage)'.
Also (within NE Gheg) une, ūn(ë).Composite form of personal pronoun u (identical to u 'self' < PAlb *we) and particle në (cf. Gk ναí, νη).
Also shpes(ë), shpezë.< *su-petno-t- (Huld, 1984: 154, in Kortlandt 1987).Alternatively, to pendë 'feather' < Lat. pinna, penna 'id.'. (Orel 429).
Alternatively ndohtë, both deverbal from ndoh 'make dirty', itself to dhjes 'to shit (on), ruin' < PIE **ǵʰed-i̯e- (Demiraj 1997: 290f.; LIV: 172).
Relatively late loanword from Lat canem or, rather, from its Balkan continuations, reflected in the lack of rhotacism in Tosk.
Borrowed < Lat pinna, penna 'feather; pair of oxen'. Second meaning is a metaphoric derivative of the latter, meaning more 'plumage'.
< IE *eh3uiom, cf. Arm jvoj (gen.) and Cze vejce. Orel, however, claims it to be a loan from Latin. Both have same etymological origin, however.

Frequently also mbar (with prefix en- '(in)to').< Pr. Alb. *bar- + unknown enlargement, related to PIE *bʰer-, though the exact basis remains unclear (o-grade seems necessary, but for a continuantion of PIE iterative *bʰor-éye/o one would expect indications of umlaut).
-zë is diminutive, but almost stable element of the word in Standard Alb.Gheg shows vo ~ ve, which according to Orel speaks for a borrowing < Latin ovum 'id'.
Also 'foot'. Borrowed < Rom *camba ~ *gamba 'leg, although direction of borrowing may be uncertain.
Goes back to PAlb *gluna dissimilated from *g(a)nuna, which is a derivative based on IE *genu- 'knee'.
Goes back to PAlb *skīw-ila, derived from *skijā > hije 'shadow' (Orel). Holm, however, prefers an IE origin in *h1eus 'burn, glow'.
Also 'rock'. From PAlb *gura continuing IE *guer- 'mountain', cf Skt gir-, Av gairi-, Lith girià 'wood', Latv dziria id and Slav *gora 'mountain, wood'.
(aor. stem reflects a different root PIE *gʷerh₃- + preverb *an-)
From PAlb *dzamba, a dialectal IE word for tooth shared with TochA, TochB, Latv, Slav, etc. Original meaning is preserved in Gk γομφος and Skt jámbha- 'peg'.
Borrowed from Lat venire. Aorist continues PAlb *erdza which is etymologically identical to Gk ερχομαι 'to come'.
gjuej besides (esp. older) gjuo(n)j and contracted gjuj.
Also 'broad'. From PAlb *saina, based on IE *s(e)h₁-i-no- 'long, late', cf. OE síd 'long, wide', Goth seiþus 'late', OIr síth 'long', Lat serus 'late', etc. (cf. Orel 133; Kroonen 2013: 435).

Original 1sg form was *vemConnection with Arm. gam '(I) come', Lat. vādō 'to go, to walk' and ON vað 'id' remains unlikely due to the unexpected vocalism. Schumacher/Matzinger (1002ff.) have now shown that it most likely belongs to *h₁ei̯- 'go' with v- (lautgesetzlich) from the Aorist.
Identical to the noun 'truth'. The alternative word 'drejtë' means 'correct, real', to /lexeme/30802/ straight'.
kâmë ~ kâmbë Loan < Romance *camba ~ *gamba (but not attested in Balkan Romance) < (Vul)Lat gamba 'leg, ankle, pastern' (itself < Grk. κάμπη)

From PAlb *glusā, further connected with IE dial. *golso- 'sound', cf also ON kall 'shout', Lith galsas 'echo', Slav golsъ 'voice'. Holm disagrees, favouring instead a root in IE *dnghuā 'tongue', cf /cognate/327/(cognate class W).
Alternative (so in Dyen) shtij/shtie has a more specialized meaning 'cast, shoot, project into sth.' (cf. e.g. Mann 1948 s.v.).
Also 'hide, bark'. From PAlb *lauk-ura derived from IE *leuk- 'to shine, to be white''. Holm disagrees, proposing a form comprising the prefix lë- + kur = loan < Lat corium 'thick skin, leather'.
North Eastern Geg: Kosovo;Loan < Turkish sarı 'yellow'. The Standard word verdhë denotes 'green'.

Orel gives the derivation from PIE *g̑ʰelh₃-u̯o- 'yellow', but Holm (p. 82) suggests alternatively to put it back to PIE *dei̯h₂- (LIV 108) 'blaze, shine', viz. *d(e)i̯h₂-lo-, cf. Alb. ditë 'day(light)' < *dih₂-to-.
Nasal lost secondary after the aorist; frequent in the same meaning non-active âjem.

Orel gives the old idea of a derivation from PIE *g̑ʰelh₃-u̯o- 'yellow', but Holm (p. 82) suggests alternatively to put it back to PIE *dei̯h₂- (LIV 108) 'blaze, shine', viz. *d(e)i̯h₂-lo-, cf. Alb. ditë 'day(light)' < *dih₂-to-.
each attested once, in reference to the same entity, which is possibly a dragon rather than a snake.
Old locative (orig. plural) of relative(-interrogative) që 'which, that'
Borrowed < Rom *manctus, based on Lat mancus 'maimed, infirm', cf also Ital manca 'left hand'.
Nasal old, frequent ëj, âj are secondary after the aorist.Frequent in meaning 'swell' in on-active  form ë(n)jtem.

Usually described by paraphrasis with rri (= 'to sit, stand, stay, remain', going back to PAlb *rina ~ OInd  ṛnoti 'to arise, to move') and adj. shtrirë 'extended, stretched, lying' to shtrij- < Pr. Alb. *strinja-, a secondary nasal present either to PIE ster- 'to strike down, flatten sb.' (LIV 597f.) or *sterh₃- 'spread, scatter' (LIV 599f.) - undecideable phonologically and semantically (thus Matzinger & Schumacher).

Usually described by paraphrasis with rri (= 'to sit, stand, stay, remain', going back to PAlb *rina ~ OInd ṛnoti 'to arise, to move') and adj. shtrirë 'extended, stretched, lying' to shtrij- < Pr. Alb. *strinja-, a secondary nasal present either to PIE ster- 'to strike down, flatten sb.' (LIV 597f.) or *sterh₃- 'spread, scatter' (LIV 599f.) - undecideable phonologically and semantically (thus Matzinger & Schumacher).
Goes back to PAlb *nera, further connected with Skt nár-, ανηρ (now husband), Arm ayr, all with identical meanings.

'live, stay'; < Pr. Alb. *rānja-, which is connected by Orel with Lith. róju, róti 'to cope, be ready', thus pointing to a root PIE **reh₁i̯-, but connected with Alb, rri 'sit, stay' it could go back to *(h₁)rei̯d- 'lean', LIV 503, Matzinger & Schumacher 994, with different stem formation and preverb *an-.
*h₁ei̯-e/o- > Early Pr.Alb. *e(i̯)-e/a- --> *e(i̯)-ā/ō- --> Late Pr.Alb. *e-e/a- > 3.sg. *i̯e --> *u̯e after the aorist (Matzinger & Schumacher 1002).

phon_form: ɡuɹˈve̝ːut, ɡuɹˈve̝ː-; ˈbe̝ːã ɡuɹˈve̝ːët, n i ˈhuɹve
notes: (lie down), beżã gourveżed, en e c’hourveż (be lying)

notes: Goes back to PAlb *nera, further connected with Skt nár-, Gk ανηρ and ClArm ayr, all with identical meanings.
Adjectival derivative of of pref ~ preh < *për-eh with eh < Pr. Alb. *a(k)ska-, a *-ske/o- formation to PIE *h₂ek̑- 'sharp'.

Late derivative of ftoh ~ ftof 'to cool, to make cold' < Pr. Alb. *wi-tāja, whose second element compares with Slav. *tajo, *tajati 'to melt', < PIE *teh₂- 'thaw, melt', here with suffix -f- < -h- < *-sk̑e-. The oppositive meaning derives from the preverb f- < *wi- < *apu- (Schumacher & Matzinger: 974).
as a geographical name in LL: 265.
irreg. pres.; reg. stems: gouveż-, goui-, gwoar-
Attested in the context '(small) stars as pattern on cloth'.

As Slavic languages do not differ (at least as to the root, not alwas as to the whole word) between swimming (of living beings) and floating (of things) it can be assumed that the proper Swadesh term contained the same root as.
The context is 'six winged angels', the author of the manuscript ordered an icon. The word comes most probably from the educated language and not from the dialect itself.
This lexeme is attested only in one manuscript, the most probable meaning of the attestation is 'statement of a witness' ('something that hears'>'something that one says in the court'?).
In the text it is used in the meaning 'heavy situation'. The root is also attested in a verbal derivative 'отѧгчитисѧ' 'take (a) burden' with a textual meaning 'take trouble'.
Substantive 'hunting'. Words with the root *lov- have in all attestations with a clear context the meaning 'fishing'.

The word 'колѣно' 'kolěno' is attested once in the corpus but its textual meaning is 'river turn'. It could be accepted as a attestation of a special meaning of the Slavic word for 'knee'. However, the gloss is uncertain, there are other possible hypotheses.
The verb 'знати' 'znati' is never attested in a context which would clearly point to the Swadesh meaning.
In Slavic the words for 'laugh' and 'mock, scorn, ridicule' contain the same root.
Attested not in a birch bark manuscript but in a graphitti in the Sofia Cathedral in Novgorod
A part of a place name. The form 'глин-' 'glin' is a contamination of *gnil- 'rot' and *glin- 'clay'. In the corpus there is also attested the infinitive of the verb 'to rot'.
Taking into account the other Slavic languages one can assume that the adjective for 'round' was derived from the root *krǫg- which is found in the attested form 'кругъ'.
The verb '(с)казати' seems to be less frequently used and has a meaning more like 'to inform'.
There is a synonym 'hrekati' but it is probably expressive and refers to the sound ('to hawk').

gloss: inhabitiant of a place 'behind the lake'
notes: Proper name with a clear structure 'person living behind the lake'. The Slavic root for 'lake' is attested in Old Novgorod texts in other place names too.
Most probably in moral or ritual sense. 'Gard' means probably 'ugly' and 'szmardech' is 'stinking'.

notes: G.pl. τούτων (stem allomorphy). Cf. αὗται 'they' (fem.), ταῦτα 'they' (neut.).  Used as the unmarked 3.pl. pronoun in the nominative. For singular forms see /lexeme/35438/. hapax, used in metaphorical sense 'worthless', but cognate forms are used for verb 'to rot' and noun 'putrefaction'  (Yoshida gives pūtē/pwtˀk for rotten; reading uncertain)
"sand, gravel", reconstructed from S šykth etc.

reconstructed from M/S šnʾk. The common C words for 'small' seem to be largely or wholly used of persons.

Orel glosses this lexeme as 'fruit-tree, fruit'. In Standard and Tosk often synonymous with dru (cognate/503/) and more and more replacing it (which itself > 'wood'). In Geg, pemë preserves the old meaning 'fruit'. Borrowing < Lat. pōmus 'fruit-tree' (~ pōmum 'fruit').
It is a derivative form 'отрокъ'. 'отрокъ' has two meanings: 'child' and 'servant'. Altogether the words occur ca. 170 times in the Canon.
non-active voice of ul 'to lower', according to Orel to Grk. eilw 'to shut in, press' and Lith. valýti 'to clean'.

There are some synonyms: 'čivìja, čuwìja', 'drъ̀ŋk', 'prъ̀nčka'. 'čivìja, čuwìja', 'drъ̀ŋk' have more specified meanings ('čivìja, čuwìja' is a stick for driving donkeys, 'drъ̀ŋk' is a tool used in bread backing). 'prъ̀nčka' is primarily a part of loom.

Together wirh Gr. κρᾱνίον, Ved. śīrṣṇá- going back to PIE *k̑roh₂sno- 'head'.

Attested in a compound *ἐμφυσάω 'breathe/blow upon' 1x at Joh 22:22.
Inf. ἀλεῖν.  Typically used of grinding σῖτος 'grain'.
G.sg. ἀγαθοῦ; ἀγαθός, ἀγαθή, ἀγαθόν.  Comparatives βελτίων, ἀμείνων, κρείττων and Superlatives ἄριστος, βέλτιστος, κράτιστος are suppletive from different stems.
Inf. φέρειν.  (Suppletive future οἴσω, aorist ἤνεγκα, perfect ἐνήνοχα < *h₁nek̑- cf. /cognate/5130/).
G.sg. παιδός. Generically ‘child' and may be masculine or feminine as to whether the child is male or female.  Meanings 'slave, servant’ are secondary.

attested as the name of the wind god in 2nd cent.
hapax; the context would also allow leg"" (not in Sims-Williams 2007)
only in the compound σπαδο-ζαγγο "on bended knee"
reconstructed from past stem ωγοτο (meaning almost but perhaps not quite certain)
younger form is σαρδο; for „(calendar/regnal) year“ see xšono/axšono, which could be a loanword from Greek xrónos
only attested with a person as object
pres. stem reconstructed from Manichaean past stem ʾwjyd
attested as the name of the moon god in 2nd cent. and later in meaning 'month' (AF maυo)
reconstructed from past stem νακανδο (hapax, used as a transitive verb)
αχασ- seems to have a slightly wider meaning 'dispute, quarrel, fight'
compound ā-morg with ā for "egg", cf. Korn (2005: 346)
used specifically in case of wood

phon_form: ˈɡlĩn; ˈpe̞nː är ˈɡlĩn, ˈpe̞nːo n ˈdǝulĩn

phoneMic: ˈɡlĩn; ˈpenː är ˈɡlĩn, ˈpenːo n ˈdǝulĩn

notes: Nom.sg. is only attested through Sumerogram IGI or Akkadogram ĪNU. The given native script form ša-a-ku-u̯a is nom.pl.
In Hittite the full grade stem (*h₂éh₁s-) was generalized.

gloss: to cut, to cut up, to cut out off

notes: intrans., < IE *iég-o-, cognate with 'ice' in /lexeme/24026/, 'cold' in /cognate/982/. Not exactly 'to freeze', but 'to cool down'. Form i-ga-it 3.sg.pret.act. (3.sg.pres.act. not attested).
Native script form ḫu-ur-nu-u̯a-an-zi is an infinitive. The 3.sg.pres. is only attested as an imperfective stem [ḫ]u-u-u̯a-ar-ni-iš-ke-ez-zi.
OH ūk, NH ammuk (taken over from the original oblique stem amm-).
maybe related to Lat. COMPUTARE, but rejected by Kloekhorst

gloss: to die, to be killed, to be eclipsed
notes: etym. dubious, maybe related to Lat. NECARE 'to kill', Gr. NEKYS 'corpse' or Toch. AK(E) (Weeks 1985: 76). Acc to Puhvel, an IE root is probable and links the form to an obscure Venetic compound. Naturally this is not a particularly pleasing link.
Form attested only once (nom.pl. wa-at-ta-e-eš). Identification with Sum. MUŠEN (Friedrich 1927:190 1) is generally accepted. The word (a diphthong stem) is probably inherited.
A zero-grade is possible, see the cognate OHG tunkal < *dhngw-lo-.

Connection with Lat. albus 'white' and ἀλφός 'dull-white leprosy' plausible, albeit the generally accepted reconstruction as *h2elbho- 'white' shows serious difficulties concerning the existence of PIE *a.Weeks discusses relation to /cognate/955/ ,white (thing) > cloud' '(1985: 20f).

The lexeme is normally spelled using the Sumerogram GÌR (Akk. ŠĒPU), e.g. nom.sg. GÌR-aš. The native script form given, pa-a-tu-u[š] is acc.pl. Also attested are instr. pa-te-et, gen.pl. pa-ta-a-an, and dat.-loc.pl. pa-ta-a-aš. According to Kloekhorst (2008:653-654) the OH forms may reflect the original athematic root noun, while the thematic pata- forms attested in NH are secondary innovations.
Lit. a participle derived from the verb ā(i)- 'to be hot'.
probably a nasal infixed verb that was trasferred to the hatrai-class.

Nom.sg. only attested with Sumerographic writing GÍD.DA-aš. Native script form reconstructed using stem attested from oblique cases: ta-lu-kán (acc.sg.), ta-lu-ga (nom./acc.n.), da-lu-ga-aš (gen.sg.).
Native script form šar-ḫu-u-u̯a-an-da-an is acc.sg.; the nom.sg. form is not attested.
*u 'hither' + *i 'come' (Weeks 1985: 154), the latter part being cognate with /cognate/2377/
Old ablauting ḫi-verb (wāk-/wakk-, typ āk-/akk- ‘to die’). Cf. tentatively Pal. wakk- ‘id.?’, too.
ur-āri (attested in OS textsalready) / u̯ar-āri (from MS texts onwards)(Med.). Pres.3sg. u̯(a)rāni shows dissimilation from original *u̯(a)rāri.
Nom.sg. is always spelled as a Sumerogram É-er, (gen.sg. É-aš). The nominative stem per- is certain from dat.-loc.sg. pé-e-ri (beside pár-ni) and abl. É-er-za beside pár-na-za.
Stem shows allomorphy between nom. stem zī- < Proto-Anatolian *ti- vs. oblique tu- < Proto-Anatolian *tu-.

Native script form ma-ni!-in-ku-e-eš (nom.pl.). In context (KUB 23.55 iv 8) the form could also be restored as a verb ma-ni!-in-ku-e-eš[-ta], but even if that restoration is correct, one would posit an adjective *maninkuu̯a- to explain the formation of the verb maninkuu̯anu- and the adverb maninkuu̯an (CHD). Cf. 'short' /lexeme/20273/

Always written using the Sumerograms LÚ.ŠU.GI. There are no syllabic writings attested, but the reconstructed stem is based on the factitive verb *mi(i̯a)ḫu(u̯a)ntaḫḫ-, mieḫuu̯andaḫḫ-, miḫuntaḫḫ- 'to make old', derived noun *mii̯aḫuu̯andatar 'old age', mii̯a(ḫ)ḫuntešš- 'to become old'.
Nom.sg. always spelled as 1-iš (OS), 1-aš (NS).  The native script form as given is reconstructed from gen.sg. ši-i-e-el, dat.-loc.sg. ši-e-da-ni, etc. Cf. CHD for full range of forms attested.
Earliest texts show an inflection nom.sg. antuu̯aḫḫaš, acc.sg. antuḫšan. Besides these, we find a thematic stem antuḫša- which must be based on the original athematic oblique antuḫš- (EDHIL).
Nom.sg. only as Sumerographic ÍD-aš; native script form reconstructed from gen.sg. ḫa-pa-aš

Nom.sg. only as Sumerographic MU.KAM-za. Stem attested in syllabic spellings of oblique case forms ú-i-it-ti (dat.-loc.sg.), ú-i-[-it-ta-an], ú-it-ta-an, ú-i-it-ta-aš (gen.pl.) and derived vocab., e.g. u̯ettandātar 'period of a year', etc.
Puhvel gives au(s)-, u(wa)-. auszi is a secondary, late form according to him. Derived from Skt. avati 'observe, notice'.
Luvian gloss. Nom.sg. NUMUN-an; the native script form has been reconstructed on the basis of the syllabic spelling of the gen.sg. u̯ar-ru-u̯a-la-na-aš.
Native script form ma-ak-la-an-ta-an is acc.sg.; the nom.sg.com. is unattested (cf. CHD L-N).

Only attested in two contexts, as a body part of bears, šāša-animals, and lions, and leopards. This may mean tail, but could be some other body part shared in common to these animals. The identification of this lexeme as TAIL is therefore not entirely certain. Cf. discussion in EDHIL.

The numeral '3' is only attested in full syllabographic spelling once: te-ri-i̯a-aš (gen.pl.; KUB 43.60 i 9 OH/NS). Elsewhere the logogram 3 is used, e.g. nom.pl. 3-e-eš. We may assume the reading underlying 3-e-eš would have been *terii̯ēš (Kloekhorst 2008:873).

The reading arma- underlying the Sumerograms ᵈEN.ZU, ITU⁽ᴷᴬᴹ⁾, or Akkadogram ᵈSÎN in Hittite is supported by derivatives like armanni- 'lunula' and names like ᵐAr-ma-zi-ti- = ᵐ˙ᵈSÎN-ma-LÚ-i-, armuu̯alai- 'to shine (of the moon)'. Cf. further notes in cognate class.
Adverbial form. As an adjective the numeral is only attested using the logographic spelling '2' taking case endings from the pronominal declension. Cf. Hoffner & Melchert (2008:156).
Oblique stem attested via dat.-loc.pl. pád-da-na-aš and pát-ta-na-aš.
Native script oblique stem form pár-ta-u-na-az is abl.; the gen.sg. is unattested.

Attested only in HL.; in CL see Sum. DUMU. Common interpretation of nimuwiza- as 'who has no (ni-) force (muwa-)'. Etymologically connected to Lyc. muwẽte- 'descendence', CL mūwa-, HL muwa- 'to overpower, dominate'.  Etymology of muwa- unclear (cf. Weiss, M. 1996. Greek μυρίος ʽcountless ʼ, Hittite mūri- ʽbunch (of fruit)ʼ, HS 109, 199-214).

Onomatopoeic verb, attested once in KUB XXXIII 120 (+119 + XXXVI 31) I 26f.: man ᵈKumarbiš ŠA ᵈAnu LÚ-natar katta pašta (27) n=aš=za duškatta n=aš=za ḫa-aḫ-ḫar-aš-ta "When Kumarbi gobbled down Anu's manhood, he rejoiced and laughed." (cf. HW² Ḫ).
Lexeme refers to a 'fleshy part of the leg' (HW² E). Further semantics and etymology are unclear.
CL ādduwa- and HL átuwa- (adj.) allow to reconstruct a PA adj. in -u̯o- which is the base of a noun *edu̯ol- 'evilness'. The latter is in turn the base of the adj. ādduwāli- (cf. Hitt. idālu-).
only CL; HL áshanantisa- (n.) 'blood-offering'?, gen.adj. of *ashanant(i)- to Hitt. ashanant- 'that of blood'
nom.sg. HL: ANNUS-si-sa-, CL: MU.KAM.-iš (nom.), uš-ša-a-ti (abl.).

Reconstructed stem is not actually attested. The form underlying the Sumerogram MUNUS-an-za, MUNUS-na-aš, etc. is an n-stem and quite likely to be reconstructed as *kuu̯an- (Kloekhorst 2008:501-505) based on the inflection and the attestation of CLuw. u̯āna- 'woman', Lyd. kãna- 'wife'.
Only HL: ha-li-i (acc.pl., BOR §11, ÇİFTLİK §17), cf. há-li-ia/iá (KARATEPE, 292); CL UD.KAM-(i)- 'day'. Hitt. attests ḫal-li-i̯a (dat.-loc.sg.) marked with the Glossenkeil.
As a finite verb only HL. CL also attests a participle ú-la-an-ti-iš (nom.sg.c.) 'dead'.
CL zārt-, HL zārti-. Luvian generalizes the oblique stem, see zart- and not **zir (cf. Hitt. gen.sg. kardiyas). HLuw. attests za+ra/i-za 'heart'.
Identification of lexeme as Luwian not assured, but supported by context, cf. Starke (1990:593) (StBoT 31).
HLuv. suwani- 'dog'. CLuv. only with Sum. UR.ZÍR-(i)-.
CL; unclear. Hurrian loanword. Cf. also Hitt. uzuḫri-. Native script form is dat.-loc.sg.
Native script form is acc.sg. Cf. nom.sg. SAG.DU-SÚ.
Native script form a-ru-ta (CL) is collective plural.

gloss: body part, probably leg or thigh
notes: Precise semantics unclear. Only CL. Native script form is abl.-instr.
Native script form is nom.-acc.sg.neut.  Also found in HL as wasu- 'good'.
assured only for CL; HL has- 'force(?)', abl.-instr. "*314"ha-sá-ti-i 'by force' KARKAMIŠ A11c §30. CL ḫāš- without final -t- (cf. Hitt. ḫaštāi-, but Lat. os).
Etymology unclear. Native script form is acc.sg. (Nom.sg. is only attested as Sumerogram with phonetic complement LÚ-iš).
CL native script form is 1.pl.pres. Cf. HLuw. hwia- 'to run, to march'.
For the reading of [ᵈE]N.ZU-aš as *Armaš 'Moon(god)' its cognacy with other Anatolian lexemes, cf. notes in cognate class.

Lexeme given by Buck (1949:234) in comparison to Lat. guttur. Somewhat dubious comparison. Tischler HEG A-K glosses as 'Partie unter dem Hals und über der Brust beim Menschen, etwa. ‘Schulter’ oder ‘Oberarm’'.
Native script form ti-it-ti-te-et is abl.-instr., cf. Tischler TEG T p.393.

In CL proper only written with Sumerogram NIMUN, but full writing found in Hitt. u̯a-ar-u̯a-al-la-na-aš (gen.sg., preceded by Glossenkeil). The stem *u̯aru̯al- is also required by CL ᵈU̯aru̯alii̯a- 'god of sowing/fertility' (ᵈU̯a-ar-u̯a-li-i̯a-an, acc.sg.) in KBo IV 11,59.
Cuneiform Luvian. Native script form is acc.sg. For meaning, cf. Carruba in Kratylos 7.65.
The long vowel resulting from the loss of the laryngeal did regularly 'lenite' a following dental stop:(mi-verb) m(a)nāti 'sees' < *mnéh₂-ti.
pasūri(ya)-? cf. ACLT: inzagan-?. Semantics unclear. Cf. notes in Melchert (1993a).
Normally written with Sumerogram ᵈUTU (± phonetic complements).
Native script form te-e-da-an is acc.sg. (cf. Tischler TEG T p.345).
Cf. iškii̯e/a- 'to smear, to daub, to salve', cf. Tischler TEG A-K p.404.
cf. also the extension in -azza- of CL, HL ura/i- (n.). Simplex ura- attested 1x in CL [u-r]a-an.

Occurs in a ritual fragment KBo 12, 123:9f.: p]iran GIŠ.MAR.GÍD.DA unuwanda (10) GIŠ ḫu-]u-u̯a-ḫur-pa-al KÙ.BABBAR GAR.RA A-NA GU₄.ḪI.A=ya "Ahead are decked-out wagons. The stick is decorated with silver and for the oxen' (cf. HW² Ḫ). Cf. also turi- 'spear, lance', CLuv. tura/i- 'stick, weapon'.
cf. i- 'to go'. Stem pa- 'go' only HL. CL attests only i- 'go' (cf. Hitt. i̯e/a- 'come, go', both ultimately from PIE *h₁ei̯- (cf. notes in cognate class). Native script form is 3.sg.imptv.
Only CL. "May not be complete. Luvian status not assured, but supported by following tarrawaūnta." Same lexeme as YELLOW /lexeme/28855/.
From *išaru-/išaru̯a- 'right-hand' with dimin. suffix -ila-? Cf. variant išaru̯ai̯(a)- from *išaru-/išaru̯a- 'right-hand' with suffix -ai̯(a)-. Cf. CL īš(ša)ra/i-, HL istra/i- 'hand'.
Only CL. "May not be complete. Luvian status not assured, but supported by following tarrawaūnta." Same lexeme as GREEN /lexeme/28855/.
Only HL. Native script form á-mu also occurs as mu due aphaeresis.

CL pī(i̯a)-, HL piya-. CL also attests a stem pāi- (3.sg.imptv. pa-a-i-ú, pa-i-ú) whose context also suggests 'give' which would be a more archaic formation (Melchert 1993a:163). Native script form pi-i̯a-at-ta is 3.sg.pret.
CL āšša- 'speak'(?) denomin. of āaš- 'mouth'; HL ásaza- is a derived iterative stem.

also buburrecë, buburdhecë, buburiçkë; boboricë, boboreshë and in other varieties with the meaning 'cockroach'.Most similar looks Romanian buburuză 'ladybug', cf. for similar Romanian - Albanian isoglosses of words containing a deminutive suffix -ză ~ -zë [~cë]: coacăză 'currant' ~ kokëzë 'little head', pupăză ~ pupëzë 'hoopoe'
Derivative to militt-/malitt- 'honey'. Native script form ma-li-⎡ri+i⎤-mi-i-sá is nom.sg.com. (MARAŞ §1i)

In Bernese German (as well as other German varieties), there are two possible translations for the English verb to hit: (i) 'schlah' /ʃlaː/, which primarily profiles the activity of wielding an instrument with the purpose of hitting somebody or something, and (ii) 'träffe' /træffə/, which primarily profiles the accomplishment of establishing physical contact between the instrument and the hit entity. I assume that you are looking for the first concept.
3 sg. An alternative lexeme, historically with the same root, is 'dåimă'.

gloss: 'Blow cold' but the basal meaning was probably 'breathe'.
Probably about wind or strong blowing.

notes: Praeteritum 2/3 sg (uncertain). Attested only in the context of 'rain'.
Two different phonetic come from different dialects.
Attested only once in the context 'shepherd stick'.
1 sg. Probably more like 'mean, have in mind'.
More like 'the, it' (German 'der, die, das') than 'this'.
Perfect sg. masculine. Probably 'calculate' (German 'rechnen') and not just 'count' (German 'żählen').
looks like Ossetic and roots from a couple of other groups
Used rather in the metaphorical meaning.
Etymologically 'frighten oneself' and probably not the Swadesh term.
Glossed as 'push (in the front of oneself)', that fits good the definition.
From (Mikalja 1649). It probably refers more to oval form.
From PIE *medʰ-i̯o-; cf. Skt. mádhya - adj. '(located in a/the) middle', subst. 'the middle'.
An alternative derivative: 'храмина'. It covers not only the meanings 'house' and 'building' but also 'home'.
An alternative lexeme is 'зажда' but it is much less frequently in the Canon.
Attestet only once, not entirely certain if Swadesh meaning.
The same pronominal root as in 'kogda', relevant only for cognate sub-classes.

Alternative lexemes could be 'стр(ѹ/ъ)гати' or 'дьрати' (and some other less frequent words). However, in texts they all refer to more violent acts connected with splitting something from something (not rarely to 'tearing off the skin').

The word 'жльтъ' is not attested in OCS. However, the derivative 'жльтѣница' 'a kind of plant with yellow flowers' and the contaminated form 'жльчь' (instead of / alongside зльчь) 'gall' show that such an adjective did exist. An alternative lexeme is 'плавъ' but it has a more specific meaning 'fair, fawn, colour of ripe cereals'.
The word is reconstructed on the base of an attested derivatives (like 'дебельство'). However, it is not entirely clear if the meaning is 'thick' or rather 'fat'.
In the Canon only verbal derivatives are attested (like 'отлъстѣти'). The adjective occurs in younger texts. However, it is not entirely clear if the meaning is 'thick' or rather 'fat'.
Lit. 'not-clean'. It is attested only in the ritual, religious, and philosophical meaning in the Canon ('impure, unclean').
There is no generic term for 'brother'; there are only words for 'older brother' and 'younger brother'.
There is no generic term for 'sister'; there are only words for 'older sister' and 'younger sister'.
There is no generic term for 'brother'; there are only words for 'older brother' and 'younger brother'.
There is no generic term for 'brother'; there are only words for 'older brother' and 'younger brother'.
There are some alternative lexemes: 'lɪ́xωj', 'paskúnnωj', 'nedóbrωj'. However, examples and russian glosses suggest that they refer to people and have additional meanings as 'evil' and 'ugly'.
probably loanword.  Cf. Gk. ἰσχίον 'hips', Hesych. ἰσχίον· ὀσφύς 'loins'.

gloss: hinder part of the body, back

notes: The form is connected a.o. with Gk. ὅλος ‘whole, complete’, Skt. śarva- ‘whole, all’, Lat. salvus ‘complete, intact’ (despite the semantic difference between 'big' and 'whole').

An alternative lexeme is 'zel' which means, however, 'morally bad, evil' (in this meaning it is used normally as attribute of people, mythological personages and their behavior) or 'very bad, bringing suffering and great problems'.

Interpreted as the instrumental plural of an adjective *ὀρνίθιος (*ὀρνιθίαφι(ν)) meaning 'decorated with birds', referring to the ornamentation of a to-no *θόρνος 'chair' in PY Ta 707.1.  The lexeme ὄρνῑς 'bird' is not otherwise attested in Mycenaean.  Cf. Attic ὄρνις (stem: ὀρνιθ-)  /lexeme/18660/.
Alternative lexeme is 'ptax', with the same root. The lexeme 'ptɪ́cʹa' is a collective noun in this variety.

gloss: to wound with the teeth (beak), bite

notes: borrowed into Hitt. (v.) marwāi- 'to blacken'(?). Possible IE cognates: ON myrkr 'dark', mjǫrkvi 'darkness', OSax. mirki, OE mierce 'dark'.
heteroclitic noun ēšḫar/išḫan-. Cf. Gk. ἔαρ ‘blood’ (rare).

gloss: bone, (fig.) strenght, a measure of lenght
notes: diphthong-stem inflection. cf. within Anatolian CLuw. ḫāš- ‘bone’ and HLuw. has- ‘force(?)’ (abl.-instr. “*314”ha-sa-ti-i ‘by force’ KARKAMIŠ A11c §30).
G.sg. ὀστέου . Attic form contracts medial -εο-.  The uncontracted form is attested by Ionic ὀστέον.
Inf. καίεσθαι. Medio-passive verb form.  Cf. καίω 'set on fire, burn' (active and transitive).  Cf. perfect passive κέκαυμαι 'be on fire, burn'.
There is an anlternative lexeme 'palátɪ' which, however, refers to a more intensive burning, producing a lot of light and high temperature.
G.sg. νέφεος. νέφος (s-stem neut.) directly continues PIE *nébʰos.  Alternative derived form νεφελή (ā-stem fem.) is synonymous.
An alternative lexeme is 'studen', it means, however, 'very cold, icy'.
'рыдати' and derivatives (attested much less frequently than 'плакати (сѧ)') is more like 'to sob, snivel'. 'сльзити' (attested much less frequently than 'плакати (сѧ)') means 'to shed tears'.

In the corpus attested with the prefix 'у-' 'u-' in the imperative. The last part of the attested word is reconstructed but the beginning of the word and the meaning fit the context of the whole text. The root is attested also in the word 'урезъкъ' 'urezŭkŭ' with a meaning 'a cut off part of something'.
absence of lenition, cf. pres.3.sg. lati of verb la- 'die' vs. pret.3.sg. lade of verb la- 'release'. Cf. also subst. lãta- 'corpse'.
HL; CL nom. sg. anim. tāwīs and coll. pl. tawa
An alternative lexeme is 'salo' [sâlɔ]. However, it seems to be slightly less general than 'mast'. 'salo' is definied as 'human or animal fat in the belly'.

First attested in the Catholicon (1499). See also brumen 'fog' attested in Julien Maunoir, Les dictionnaires français-breton et breton- français (1659), which is considered as the first work of Early Modern Breton. All other Breton words denoting 'fog' are attested even later.
Attested in Latin script peturpursus 'four-footed' (dat.pl., VIb 11) < *kʷetur-pōd- 'quadriped' (cf. Gr. τετράπους, Ved. cā́tuṣpad-, Lat. quadrupēs).
clv, un tamm freuzh sgv ‘a piece of fruit’

Lyc. pije- is the result of the  generalization of *bija- from the 3.pl. *bijanti, see pres.3.sg. *bijati near the form *bai (*#b  > #p ). The formation of the *bijanti is still unclear. This could be comparable to 3.sg. dai 'put' and 3.pl. tianzi, tiyanzi 'they put' - This would mean that the ablaut *o / Ø of the root of the ḫi-Verben (which undergo ablaut) has been used for a verb of different origin. In particular, protoluv. *píi̯ōi is an innovation(cf. HL pres.3.sg. *piyai (: DARE-i), CL pret.3.sg. piyatta) which replaced the old *pṓi (: Hitt. pāi 'he gives') < *pe-Hói̯-ei. Cf. Lyc. pibi(je)- 'to give'.

gloss: to turn, to come to mind, to change (opinion, confession), to start

notes: etymologically cognate with CL and Hitt. apā- 'that'. PA *obṓ-.
G.sg. τούτου (stem allomorphy). Cf. αὕτη 'she', τοῦτο 'it'.

The definite article and the deictic particle se constitute a discontinuous marker used as an attributive demonstrative. The phrase consists of article + noun + particle, e.g. an den man 'this man', an fest man 'this festival'. Note that Middle Breton has a threefold deictic system: an ... man 'here (near me) / this', an ... se 'there (near you) / that', an ... hont 'yonder'.
The most frequently used derivative. However, there is also a form without the prefix (ѩти) and forms with other prefixes.

gloss: to tie, to tie up, to fasten

notes: Root /enʦ-/, surely cognate with Toch. B /enk-/, though details remain difficult. Sense closer in many contexts to 'grasp, seize', but no more "neutral" verb for 'take' attested.
Attested 1x with preverb ἐπι- in ἐπιράπτει '(s)he sews on' (Mk 2:21).
One manuscript contains the word 'ледѧны' 'ledęny' 'made of ice'. However, the text is written in Church Slavic with only some traces of its Novgorod origin.

gloss: having a warm, but not hot, temperature, lukewarm

notes: Native script: arvia (acc.pl., Ia 3, 9, 26, Ib 3, 6, IIa, 18, 24), aruvia (acc.pl., III 31), arviu (acc.pl., Ia 12, 16, 23, Ib 25, 28, 32, 43, IIa 6, 11, 12, IIb 8, 29). Latin script: aruio (acc.pl., VIa, 56, 58, VIb 1, 3, 29, 22, 44, 45, VIIa 4, 7, 42, 53). In context this lexeme is usually interpreted as 'guts' (cf. Untermann 2000:125-126) as a part of the sacrificial animal. Alternatively is an etymological interpretation as 'grain' is also possible by assuming it comes from the same root as 'to plough' (cf. de Vaan 2008:56 s.v. arvum 'ploughed land').
The dił-forms would have been loaned from Old Persian before *rd > l
'important, powerful', etym. difficult, maybe IE *(h)nek- 'to seize, carry'

The verb is consistently spelled with the syllabogram ḪAR, which can be read as both ḫar and ḫur. There is some debate over whether the stem should be read as ḫarn- or ḫurn-. The form šiš, which is borrowed from colloquial Persian, is not often used by the interviewed speaker, but is increasingly used in the language generally, especially by younger members of the language community.
The diphthong-like segment in the first syllable of this word is [a̝e̯] phonetically, and it contrasts with ay [aj] (e.g., xwayšk ‘sister’) as well as ē [eː] (e.g., pēšt ‘back’).
It is possible that the underlying form of the v in this word is actually /f/, since [v] has a very restricted distribution in the language.
Some speakers of this variety, but not the interviewed speaker, use the form dẅıyēs.

The synonyms galü and halq, either of which may be be borrowed from Persian, are not often used by the interviewed speaker, but are increasingly used in the language generally, especially by younger members of the language community. In all words, the phoneme g in this position (after a vowel at the end of a word) is pronounced as a velar approximant with significant closure, but no actual spirantization.
The word mırk is also used for ‘elbow’, but tends to be used in descriptive or figurative speech; wheras balačaq is more strictly anatomical.
The term dıḷ refers to the upper part of the belly, and also to the internal organs, especially the stomach. The word zıg refers to the belly and the abdomen.

The term dıḷ refers to the upper part of the belly, and also to the internal organs, especially the stomach. The borrowed word mēda is a more exact anatomical term.

Both qwıl and pā are used commonly (by the speaker and in the language community generally) for the meaning ‘foot/leg’. The term pā, which comes from Persian, is dominant in formal contexts, and is most common among urban, educated, and younger speakers of the language.

The term zānü, which is similar to Persian zānu, is also used other speakers of this variety, but is not often used by the interviewed speaker. The words kaškıḷa and zırānü are both common and have the exact same meaning. The word kaškıḷa is cognate for the word 'kneecap' in other Iranic varieties, for example Bakhtiari kaškak.

Both qwıl and pā are used commonly (by the speaker and in the language community generally) for the meaning ‘foot/leg’. The term pā, which comes from Persian, is dominant in formal contexts, and is most common among urban, educated, and younger speakers of the language.

The word mēz is the most common term in the area. The word čwıṛ, which is also used by some families, including the interviewed speaker, looks similar to the word used by Lori speakers in the same region.

The term qaḷb, which is borrowed from Arabic via Persian, is a more strictly anatomical for ‘heart’. The older term dıḷ also refers to this organ, but has a broader semantic range and also includes the inside of the thorax and upper abdomen generally, and is also used figuratively as the seat of emotion.
Some speakers of this variety, but not the interviewed speaker, use the form pyāg.

Both zāṛū and bača are used commonly (by the speaker and in the language community generally). The term bača, which comes from Persian, is dominant in formal contexts, and is most common among urban, educated, and younger speakers of the language.
Some other speakers of this variety, and especially older speakers, use the form xwayšıg.

The term kwıṛ, which also means ‘boy’, is associated with informal contexts, wheras the borrowed Persian term dāmād ‘groom, son-in-law/brother-in-law’ is associated with formal contexts. The cognate term in this variety, zāmā, means ‘son-in-law/brother-in-law’ only.

The term dẅat, which also means ‘girl’, is associated with informal contexts, wheras the borrowed Arabic (via Persian) term arūs (with the variant ırūs found especially among older speakers) is associated with formal contexts.

Present indivative 3 sg., cf. also dibu preterite 3 sg. 'he/she came'. The paradigm of the verb TO COME is highly suppletive in Brittonic. The forms of the present indicative are based on PIE *h₂ag̑- in Middle and Modern Welsh, and also in Middle Cornish and Breton. In addition to this, Old and Middle Welsh possess compounds consisting of *tu- + bot 'to be' (PIE *bʰu̯eh₂-). The original meaning of these forms probably was 'to be present' (Schumacher 2004, 192, note d), Schumacher 2011, 186). Evans (1964, 133) lists MW dybyd etc. as "consuetudinal present and future", MW dybu as "preterite 2". This additional notion could be present in the OW forms as well. In view of Middle Welsh, the existence of forms based on Proto-Celtic *ag- seems probable. These forms most likely conveyed the basic meaning of COMING, without any additional notions. They are not attested in Old Welsh, however, due to the fragmentary nature of the corpus.

This may strike speakers of many varieties of English as unusual, but needs to be seen in the context of significant differences between different varieties of English worldwide.  Highly relevant is that in the variety of English targeted here, i.e. standard British English and following majority usage in England, the lexemes 'ill' and 'unwell' are very widely used, where other varieties use 'sick'.  This allows a particular usage of '(being) sick', in the specific sense of vomiting, especially in the most common aspectual and tense uses.  So in this specific variety, in the default, unmarked register, speakers most often use formulations like "S/he has been sick" to mean not "S/he has been ill" (as they would normally refer to a period of ill health), but to mean specifically "S/he has (just) vomited":  Likewise, normal usage would be: "Please stop the car, I’m going to be sick.", meaning specifically that the speaker felt s/he was about to vomit.

The lexeme 'vomit' in this variety has rather narrower register uses, slightly elevated ad 'medical'.  There are also a host of other familiar register lexemes, as in other varieties of English.

Although also the name of the internal organ 'stomach', in the variety of English targeted here, i.e. standard British English and following majority usage in England, the word 'stomach' has broadened to refer to the abdomen in general, and is has become the default, unmarked word for the target sense here.  The lexeme 'belly' is more marked in register, often with overtones of a protruding 'pot belly'..
